  <span id="freeText3564065982026544646" style="display:none">I picked up this book hoping to find another murder-mystery author I could enjoy as much as I do Christie. <br />This book takes place in a nursing home for the invalid. Where people are killed off one after the other is what seem like accidents. Inspector Dalgliesh slowly tries to pu pieces together and get to the bottom of the killings.<br />The plot is tedious. The narrative creaks and groans and whimpers and almost left me in a stupor.<br />And having reached the end of the book I'm surprised I made it till the last page.<br /> <br />I was thinking of trying another of her books - a more popular one - and then I read this article : where she thinks of Christie as "such a bad writer" : "<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2012/jun/02/archive-1986-pd-james-crime-writer">http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian...</a>&quot;<br />I don't think I'd enjoy P.D. James - her sensibilities about what makes a good murder-mystery are obviously starkly different from mine.</span>
